"""
MKT Context — Luke chapter 8 (all 56 verses)
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/luke.json
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-luke-8-8.py
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new verse entries without overwriting already-present keys — safe to re-run.
    # CHANGE? If commentary JSON structure changes from {ch:{v:html}}, update this traversal.
    # VERIFY: Re-running the script should produce identical output (no duplicate or overwritten entries).
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

LUKE_CH8 = {
"8": {
"1": "<p>The Galilean tour 'through cities and villages' reflects itinerant teaching patterns known from both Cynic philosophers and Jewish popular teachers. Jesus traveling with the Twelve signals formal rabbinic-style discipleship formation. The phrase 'proclaiming and bringing the good news of the kingdom' (euangelizomenos) echoes imperial messenger vocabulary — emperors sent heralds proclaiming good news (euangelia) of military victory or dynastic succession. Jesus's kingdom proclamation implicitly counters imperial claims to define 'good news.'</p>",
"2": "<p>Mary Magdalene's identification by hometown (Magdala, a prosperous fishing town on the western shore of the Sea of Galilee) was a common naming convention for women without patronymic identification. 'From whom seven demons had gone out' indicates severe possession; seven was associated with completeness in Jewish numerology (Gen 2:2; Lev 4:6; Prov 6:16), suggesting total domination and therefore total deliverance. Her prominence here (named first) and in the resurrection narratives is remarkable given women's limited legal standing as witnesses in first-century Jewish law (m. Rosh Hashana 1.8; m. Sanhedrin 3.4).</p>",
"3": "<p>Joanna's identification as wife of Chuza, Herod Antipas's household manager (epitropos, a term for the steward of a royal estate), places her in the upper economic tier of Galilean society. That a woman from Herod's own administrative circle followed Jesus reflects the movement's social breadth and its penetration into the governing class. The note that these women 'provided for them from their own resources' (diakonoun autois ek tōn hyparchontōn autais) indicates financial patronage — women supporters maintaining the mission. This inverts normal Greco-Roman patronage conventions where wealthy men sustained itinerant philosophers.</p>",
"4": "<p>The crowd 'coming to him from every city' indicates Jesus's movement had spread beyond local synagogue contexts into a regional phenomenon. Parables (Greek: parabolē; Hebrew: māšāl) functioned in Jewish tradition as wisdom riddles, prophetic allegories, and ethical exemplars — used extensively in rabbinic literature to interpret Torah. The parable of the sower belongs to agricultural wisdom discourse familiar in both Jewish and Greco-Roman rural contexts. The multicity crowd already signals a receptivity that contrasts with the subsequent parable's fourfold soil typology.</p>",
"5": "<p>Palestinian agriculture often involved broadcast sowing before plowing — seed was scattered, then the field plowed to cover it. The 'path' (hodos) refers to a track worn hard by foot traffic through the field boundaries. Birds eating exposed seed was a recognized agricultural hazard. These fourfold soil types would resonate immediately with any agrarian audience in first-century Galilee, where subsistence farming and its uncertainties were immediate daily realities for most hearers.</p>",
"6": "<p>Rocky ground (petra) in Palestinian agriculture often meant a thin layer of soil over limestone bedrock — common throughout the Galilee hill country. Such ground warms quickly in spring (producing fast germination) but cannot sustain deep roots. The moisture metaphor reflects the Mediterranean dry season: crops that germinate in winter rains wilt without established roots by April–May, when the khamsin (hot east wind) arrives. Any Galilean farmer understood the phenomenon immediately.</p>",
"7": "<p>Thorns (akanthai) — likely Ononis spinosa, Paliurus spina-christi, or similar thorny scrub common in Palestinian fields — competed aggressively with grain crops. Ancient agricultural manuals (Columella, Theophrastus's Enquiry into Plants) recognized weed competition as a primary cause of yield loss. The 'choking' image captures how thorns grow tall and shade out shorter grain plants, winning the competition for light and moisture during the critical growing weeks.</p>",
"8": "<p>A hundredfold yield (hekatontaplasiona) would be extraordinary — ancient grain yields averaged 4:1 to 10:1 in Mediterranean agriculture. Some papyrus records from Egypt show exceptional yields of 50:1–100:1 in very fertile Nile Delta soil, but these were notable rarities. The exaggerated yield signals eschatological abundance — the kingdom's harvest exceeds normal agricultural expectation. 'He who has ears to hear, let him hear' echoes prophetic summons to heed divine speech (Deut 29:4; Isa 6:10; Jer 5:21; Ezek 12:2), marking this as more than agricultural wisdom.</p>",
"9": "<p>The disciples' private inquiry reflects a common pedagogical pattern in Jewish wisdom tradition where public teaching was followed by private elaboration for the inner circle. Qumran scrolls reveal a similar two-tier system: public teaching for the many, hidden mysteries (razim) reserved for the community's initiated members (1QS IV.6; 1QpHab VII.1-5). The disciples' question about meaning — 'what does this parable mean?' — signals that parabolic speech was not self-interpreting even to insiders.</p>",
"10": "<p>Jesus's citation of Isaiah 6:9 ('seeing they may not see') situates his parabolic method in the prophetic tradition of hardened hearts. Isaiah's commissioning depicted a paradoxical ministry in which proclamation would simultaneously reveal and conceal. The 'mysteries of the kingdom' (mysteria tēs basileias) uses mystērion — which in Jewish apocalyptic literature (Daniel 2; 1 Enoch; Qumran pesharim) referred to divine secrets revealed to the righteous remnant while hidden from outsiders. The parables function as pesher (interpretive key) only for those granted eschatological understanding.</p>",
"11": "<p>The interpretive identification 'the seed is the word of God' transforms the agricultural parable into an allegory about reception of Torah-like divine teaching. Jewish wisdom tradition regularly compared divine instruction to seed, rain, and water that produces growth (Isa 55:10-11; Deut 32:2; Sir 24:23-29). This intertextual framework would have been recognizable to Jewish audiences trained in midrashic interpretation of nature-wisdom sayings.</p>",
"12": "<p>The devil (diabolos) snatching seed from the heart echoes the cosmic adversary figure in Jewish apocalyptic literature — the satan of Job 1-2, Mastema of Jubilees 11:11 (who explicitly sends birds to eat seed sown by farmers — a striking parallel to this parable), and Belial of the Dead Sea Scrolls. The pneumatic warfare behind resistance to the word would have resonated with Second Temple readers familiar with these traditions about the cosmic adversary's attack on Israel's receptivity to divine teaching.</p>",
"13": "<p>The shallow-rooted hearer who falls away 'in time of testing' (en kairō peirasmou) uses peirasmos — the same word as the Lord's Prayer's 'lead us not into temptation/testing.' In the early Christian context, persecution and social pressure to return to Jewish or pagan community norms constituted the primary form of apostasy-inducing testing. Luke's Diaspora readers (likely including Theophilus and his circle) would understand this as describing defection under social or legal pressure from the surrounding Roman or Jewish community.</p>",
"14": "<p>The thorns-choked hearer describes someone overwhelmed by 'cares and riches and pleasures of life' — a three-term cluster that maps closely to Hellenistic philosophical catalogues of obstacles to philosophy. Stoic and Epicurean teachers warned against anxiety (merimna), wealth-distraction (ploutos), and pleasure-pursuit (hēdonē) as enemies of rational virtue and true flourishing. Luke's audience in Hellenistic cities would hear this in conversation with that tradition, even while Jesus grounds it in kingdom-reception rather than philosophical virtue.</p>",
"15": "<p>The 'good and honest heart' (kardia kalē kai agathē) uses kalos kagathos — the classical aristocratic ideal of integrated moral character, combining noble appearance and virtuous action. The phrase was the highest compliment in Greek civic culture. Luke appropriates this Hellenistic virtue term for the kingdom-ready person, signaling to Greco-Roman readers that authentic kingdom reception fulfills what their philosophical tradition was reaching for. 'Patient endurance' (hypomonē) is the Stoic virtue of steadfast bearing-under-trial, here redirected toward faithful kingdom perseverance through opposition.</p>",
"16": "<p>The lamp-under-vessel saying (slightly different in Matt 5:15 and Mark 4:21) uses domestic details familiar to any first-century hearer. The 'vessel' (skeuos) could be a clay storage jar used to smother and preserve embers overnight — a practical domestic technique. The lampstand (lychnia) was typically a small terracotta or bronze oil lamp placed on a stand to maximize light distribution. The saying assumes a single-room Palestinian house where one lamp provides light for all occupants — every household detail confirms the universal reach of the lamp's function.</p>",
"17": "<p>The principle that 'nothing hidden will not be made manifest' draws on Jewish wisdom tradition about divine omniscience (Pss 44:21; 90:8; Sir 1:30; 17:15-20) and apocalyptic traditions about the final judgment revealing all things (1 Enoch 63:3; 2 Bar 83:2). The Qumran community held a similar theology: hidden sins would be disclosed at the eschatological judgment (1QS IV.11-14). In the immediate context, the saying reinforces that the parables' hidden meanings are not permanently concealed — revelation is the goal, not the concealment.</p>",
"18": "<p>'To the one who has, more will be given' reflects an economic principle familiar in Greco-Roman patron-client relations — those with existing social capital receive more gifts; those without cannot maintain what little they have. Jesus appropriates this observable economic dynamic to describe spiritual receptivity: the parabolic teaching simultaneously enriches those prepared to receive and leaves unreceptive hearers without even what they seemed to have. The saying is simultaneously a warning and a promise, depending on the hearer's posture.</p>",
"19": "<p>Jesus's mother and brothers appear together as a family unit — consistent with Jewish extended family structures where adult brothers remained in the household or clustered together. That 'they could not reach him because of the crowd' indicates the scale of Jesus's Galilean movement. The family's arrival likely reflects concern about Jesus's erratic activity (Mark 3:21 explicitly says they came 'to seize him, for they were saying he is out of his mind,' though Luke omits this detail).</p>",
"20": "<p>The relay communication ('someone told him') reflects crowd-communication patterns in large gatherings. Physical proximity to the rabbi was essential for Jewish discipleship — students sat at the feet of their teacher (Acts 22:3; Luke 10:39). The contrast between biological family 'standing outside' and disciples inside listening creates the spatial frame for Jesus's redefinition of family: insiders are those who hear, not those who share bloodlines.</p>",
"21": "<p>Redefining family by hearing and doing the word echoes Deuteronomic covenantal language — the people of God are constituted by obedience to Torah (Deut 6:4-9; 30:14). The Dead Sea Scrolls community similarly reconstituted family structures around covenant: members called each other 'brothers' (achim) in the covenant community and certain obligations to biological family were subordinated to community obligations (1QS I.1-17). Jesus's redefinition creates a new covenant community whose kinship is obedience rather than biological descent.</p>",
"22": "<p>The Sea of Galilee (a freshwater lake, 13 miles long, 8 miles wide, 680 feet below sea level, surrounded by hills up to 2,000 feet) was subject to sudden violent storms funneled by the surrounding topography. Cool air from the surrounding heights could rapidly displace warm air over the lake's surface, generating squalls with little warning — a phenomenon well-known to local fishermen. A crossing from the western shore (Capernaum region) to the eastern (Decapolis) side would take several hours depending on wind conditions.</p>",
"23": "<p>Mediterranean and Galilean storms (lailaps anemon, a squall of wind) could descend rapidly from the Golan Heights east of the lake, funnel through the valleys, and whip the shallow lake surface into dangerous swells. That experienced fishermen (several of the Twelve) experienced genuine fear indicates the storm's severity — professionals who knew the lake well were alarmed. Jesus sleeping (as Jonah slept in Jon 1:5) during the storm creates a deliberate literary-typological parallel: the prophet asleep in the boat while storm threatens all aboard.</p>",
"24": "<p>The disciples' address 'Master, Master' (Epistata, Epistata) uses Luke's unique term for Jesus — not Mark's 'Teacher' (Didaskalos) or Matthew's 'Lord' (Kyrios), but a word meaning overseer or commander with military-administrative connotations. The command to wind and water uses the same rebuke vocabulary (epitimaō) used in exorcisms — wind and water respond to Jesus's authoritative word as demonic forces do. The sudden complete calm (galēnē) was immediately observable to all aboard, creating the distinctive double-sign of command-followed-by-immediate-obedience.</p>",
"25": "<p>'Where is your faith?' — The question assumes the disciples had faith sufficient to call on Jesus but not sufficient to trust during the storm itself. In Jewish tradition, faith and fear were contrasting postures before divine power (Exod 14:31; Ps 27:1-3; Isa 7:9). The disciples' question 'Who then is this?' echoes the universal Jewish question about divine identity — in Jewish scripture, only God controls wind and sea (Ps 89:9; 107:29; Job 38:8-11). The question positions Jesus in the domain of YHWH's exclusive power over creation's chaotic forces.</p>",
"26": "<p>The region of the Gerasenes (or Gadarenes in some manuscripts — textual variants indicate uncertainty about exact location near the eastern shore) was Gentile Decapolis territory. The Decapolis ('Ten Cities') was a league of Hellenized cities established after Pompey's eastern campaigns (63 BCE), featuring Greek urban culture, Roman administration, and predominantly Gentile population. Jesus's crossing is a significant geographical boundary-transgression from Jewish to Gentile territory, anticipating the Acts mission pattern where the gospel crosses ethnic boundaries.</p>",
"27": "<p>The demoniac 'from the city' living in tombs reflects Jewish impurity concerns — tombs rendered a person ritually unclean (Num 19:11-16; m. Ohalot throughout). Living among tombs further marks him as socially dead, permanently excluded from community life. His nakedness (gymnos) in public violated strong Mediterranean honor-shame conventions — shame in the ancient world was powerfully connected to covering the body (Gen 3:7; Ezek 16:8). His chronic condition beyond conventional treatment marks him as a limit-case that only divine power can address.</p>",
"28": "<p>The demon's address 'Son of the Most High God' (huie tou theou tou hypsistou) uses the divine title hypsistos — appearing in both Jewish scripture (Gen 14:18-20; Ps 78:35; Dan 3:26) and Hellenistic syncretistic religion as a transcendent divine title acceptable across religious traditions. 'Do not torment me' assumes knowledge of Jesus's authority to inflict eschatological judgment on demonic beings — consistent with Jewish apocalyptic expectations that at the end of days, demons would be bound and judged (1 Enoch 54:1-6; Testament of Solomon; Jude 6).</p>",
"29": "<p>The iterative description of the spirit seizing the man (imperfect tense in the Greek — repeated episodes) and the community's failed attempts at restraint with chains and shackles establishes the demon's superior strength over human means of control. The wilderness (erēmos) as the demon's preferred domain reflects Jewish tradition: the wilderness was the realm of unclean spirits (Isa 13:21; 34:14; Lev 16:10 LXX — Azazel goes to the wilderness; 1 Enoch 10:4-5 — fallen angels bound in the wilderness). The community's sustained failure over an extended period heightens the significance of Jesus's effortless command.</p>",
"30": "<p>'Legion' as the demon's name (a Roman military unit of 3,000–6,000 soldiers) carried politically charged connotations in Roman-occupied Palestine. Roman legions occupied Judea and Galilee; the Fourth Scythian Legion was stationed in Syria. Whether or not anti-Roman political symbolism is primary, the name explains the plurality ('many demons had entered him') and would register to any first-century hearer familiar with Roman military organization. The name functions as both self-identification and explanation of the community's inability to contain one man's demonically multiplied strength.</p>",
"31": "<p>The 'abyss' (abyssos) — the place the demons begged not to be sent — is a technical term in Jewish apocalyptic for the place of imprisoned demons awaiting final judgment (1 Enoch 10:4-6; 18:11-16; 21:1-10; cf. Rev 9:1-2; 20:1-3). The demons' request anticipates the Matthean parallel's explicit formulation: 'Have you come to torment us before the time?' (Matt 8:29) — indicating shared tradition about the premature timing of demonic eschatological judgment. Their fear of the abyss signals awareness that Jesus possesses judgment authority.</p>",
"32": "<p>A herd of pigs (choiron) feeding on the hillside locates the story unmistakably in Gentile territory — pigs were ritually impure under Torah (Lev 11:7-8) and Jewish farmers did not raise them commercially. The pigs' presence is assumed without explanation because the Gentile context makes it unremarkable. The demons' request to enter the pigs and Jesus's permission reflects tradition about demonic need to inhabit living bodies (cf. Matt 12:43-45, where unclean spirits seek 'resting places' when expelled) — the request shows they know their alternatives are the bodies or the abyss.</p>",
"33": "<p>The stampede of pigs into the lake and their drowning was economically devastating — a large herd represented significant capital investment. The lake as ultimate destination echoes the sea as chaos-boundary in Jewish cosmology (Gen 1:2; Ps 93:3-4; Isa 57:20) and the association of the abyss with chaotic waters (Gen 7:11; Rev 20:1). The lake-drowning may signal that the demons found their abyss-imprisonment despite their request — the waters of chaos-judgment swallowing them along with the pigs.</p>",
"34": "<p>The herdsmen's flight to report in both city and countryside reflects the social networks by which information spread in first-century Palestinian culture — no mass communication existed beyond the spoken word relayed through kinship and trade networks. Their report would carry immediate economic implications (whose pigs? who owns the loss?) alongside supernatural implications (who has this power?) in a community already familiar with the possessed man as a local intractable problem.</p>",
"35": "<p>'Sitting at the feet of Jesus' (para tous podas tou Iēsou) is the posture of formal Jewish discipleship (Acts 22:3, Paul at Gamaliel's feet; Luke 10:39, Mary at Jesus's feet). This detail signals the man's transformation into a disciple. 'Clothed and in his right mind' (sōphrona) — sōphrōn describes the Stoic-Platonic ideal of self-controlled rational judgment — Luke uses this philosophical virtue term to describe restored humanity. The fear of the witnesses contrasts with the man's calm restoration: the crowd's fear is the natural response to divine power they cannot categorize.</p>",
"36": "<p>'How the demon-possessed man had been healed' — the verb sōzō (save/heal/make whole) appears in the report. The same word used for eschatological salvation throughout Luke-Acts is used here for physical-spiritual restoration. Luke's consistent deployment of sōzō across healing and salvation contexts reflects a theological unity: the divine action that restores the body and the divine action that saves the soul are aspects of the single comprehensive shalom of the kingdom.</p>",
"37": "<p>The entire Gerasene population asking Jesus to leave reflects economic loss (the pigs) and overwhelming fear (phobō megalō, great fear). In honor-shame culture, great fear before supernatural power was appropriate — it acknowledged a force beyond human control. Paradoxically, the fear that should produce worship produces rejection and a request for departure. Jesus's departure without resistance reflects his pattern of not imposing his presence on unwilling communities — consistent with Luke's mission theology where rejection becomes the occasion for moving to new receptive territory.</p>",
"38": "<p>The healed man's request to remain with Jesus (einai syn autō) uses the formal language of discipleship in Luke-Acts — 'being with' Jesus describes the qualification of the Twelve (Acts 1:21-22: 'the men who accompanied us during all the time the Lord Jesus went in and out among us'). Jesus's refusal to grant this request is the only case in the Synoptics where Jesus explicitly declines a request to follow. The Gentile man is instead commissioned as a witness in his own Gentile community — the first Gentile evangelist, foreshadowing the Acts 10-11 pattern.</p>",
"39": "<p>The command to 'return to your home and declare how much God has done for you' and the man's proclamation 'throughout the whole city how much Jesus had done for him' creates narrative equivalence: what God does = what Jesus does. Luke makes this theological identification through juxtaposition — the man obeys the Jesus-command but reports the Jesus-action as God's action. The Decapolis became one of the earliest regions of early Christian mission (cf. Mark 7:31-37, return to Decapolis), and this story provides the narrative root of that mission.</p>",
"40": "<p>Jesus's return to the Galilean (western) shore is met by a welcoming crowd who 'were all waiting for him' — a stark contrast to the Gerasene rejection. The Jewish Galilean crowd's welcome creates narrative contrast with the Gentile community's rejection, reflecting the Acts pattern where initial Jewish receptivity and Gentile rejection (or vice versa) alternate throughout the mission. The sequence of storm-crossing, Gerasene exorcism, and return creates a geographical unit marking Jesus's first intentional Gentile territory engagement.</p>",
"41": "<p>Jairus is identified as a synagogue ruler (archisunagōgos) — a lay administrative officer responsible for physical management of the synagogue building and coordination of worship services. The role carried significant community status in first-century Jewish towns. His prostration before Jesus (pesōn para tous podas Iēsou, falling at Jesus's feet) is profound public deference — a prominent community leader subordinating himself to an itinerant teacher before the watching crowd. This is the posture of petition to a social superior, dramatically reversing the expected status relationship.</p>",
"42": "<p>The daughter's age of twelve years is significant in multiple cultural registers. Twelve was the threshold of Jewish religious majority and marriage eligibility for girls (m. Niddah 5.6-7; m. Sota 3.8; b. Ketubot 39b). She was precisely at the age of social transition into full covenantal and social membership. Her death at this threshold represents acute tragedy — the loss of a daughter at her marriage-eligibility moment. Jairus's urgency ('she was dying,' the present-ongoing imperfect) is heightened by the timing. The narrative pairing of the twelve-year-old daughter with the twelve-year hemorrhage woman is deliberate Lukan literary architecture.</p>",
"43": "<p>The hemorrhaging woman's twelve-year flow of blood (precisely the duration of Jairus's daughter's life) creates a deliberate narrative linkage Luke preserves from Mark. The condition (likely uterine hemorrhage) rendered her permanently ritually impure under Levitical law (Lev 15:19-30) — contact with her would transfer impurity to others, making her a social and cultic liability. She had spent her financial resources on physicians — Luke (the physician, Col 4:14) softens Mark's critical 'suffered under many physicians,' removing the blame element while preserving the financial exhaustion detail.</p>",
"44": "<p>Her approach from behind to touch the fringe (kraspedon) of Jesus's garment reflects both her social marginalization (approaching from behind avoids face-to-face contact that would make the impurity-transfer explicit) and theological sophistication. The fringe or tassel (Hebrew: tzitzit) was worn on the four corners of a garment as a Torah commandment (Num 15:38-40; Deut 22:12) — touching the tzitzit of a holy man was understood to invoke healing power (cf. Mal 4:2 LXX 'sun of righteousness with healing in its wings/kraspedon'). Her act is scripturally informed, not merely superstitious.</p>",
"45": "<p>'Who was it who touched me?' — the question seems puzzling given the crowd pressing in on Jesus. The disciples' reasonable objection ('the crowds surround you and are pressing in') reflects normal crowd-contact dynamics. But Jesus's question distinguishes between impersonal crowd-press and intentional faith-contact — the distinction between mechanical proximity and purposive faith-engagement. Peter's response (as spokesman for the Twelve) demonstrates the disciples' still-limited perception of what just occurred. The distinction Jesus insists upon is invisible to crowd-level observation.</p>",
"46": "<p>'Power had gone out from me' (dunamis exelēlythen ap' emou) — the concept of dunamis flowing from a holy person is known in Jewish traditions regarding the Spirit's operation through prophets and in Hellenistic religious contexts regarding divine men (theios anēr). The power's unidirectional flow (out from Jesus, into the woman) is noted as involuntary in one sense yet recognized by Jesus — he knew it happened before the woman identified herself. This verse uniquely describes a power-transfer mechanism not explicitly described elsewhere in the Synoptic healing narratives.</p>",
"47": "<p>The woman's 'trembling' (tremousa) and falling before Jesus reflect the terror appropriate to encountering numinous power — the same response described in OT theophanies (Dan 10:7-10; 1 Kgs 19:3; Isa 6:5; Ezek 1:28). Her public declaration 'in the presence of all the people' forces a public testimony that her healing is socially confirmed and her impurity-based isolation is ended. Luke emphasizes this public restoration — the woman is reintegrated into the community by Jesus's explicit public acknowledgment before the crowd.</p>",
"48": "<p>'Daughter, your faith has made you well' (hē pistis sou sesōken se) — sōzō again, the salvation-healing verb. The address 'daughter' (thygater) is warm, familial, and occurs rarely in Jesus's direct speech — it confirms her belonging within the covenant community after years of exclusion. 'Go in peace' (eis eirēnēn) uses the Hebrew shalom formula of comprehensive covenantal well-being — marking her complete restoration, not merely physical healing but full social, ritual, and communal reinstatement to the people of God.</p>",
"49": "<p>The messenger arriving while Jesus is still speaking ('someone from the synagogue ruler's house') and the news 'your daughter is dead; do not trouble the teacher' reflects ancient medical understanding — once death was confirmed (no breathing, cold, fixed eyes), physicians' work was finished. The message frames it in patron-client terms: don't burden (skyllō, trouble/bother/distract) the teacher with a now-hopeless case. The social calculus assumes that death ends the therapeutic relationship and places further imposition outside the bounds of appropriate client behavior.</p>",
"50": "<p>'Do not fear, only believe, and she will be well/saved' (sōthēsetai) — the future passive of sōzō continues the salvation-healing vocabulary through the frame of apparent impossibility. The parallelism of fear (phobeō) and faith (pisteuō) is a consistent Lukan structural pair: in Luke 1:12-13, 1:29-30, 2:9-10, 5:10, and here, fear is the natural response to divine encounter and faith is the called-for reorientation that receives divine action. The promise is made before any observable evidence — pure verbal promise against the reported evidence of death.</p>",
"51": "<p>Jesus's restriction of witnesses to Peter, John, James, and the parents follows the Jewish evidentiary minimum of two witnesses (Deut 19:15) and the inner-circle pattern seen at the Transfiguration (Luke 9:28). The three disciples and two parents = five witnesses — more than adequate under Torah law for legal testimony. The exclusion of the wider crowd prevents a premature public spectacle while ensuring sufficient witness coverage for what will occur — Jesus controls the timing and scope of disclosure throughout his ministry.</p>",
"52": "<p>Professional mourners (wailing and beating breast) were hired immediately upon death in Jewish custom — rapid burial was required in the Palestinian climate (within the same day if possible; cf. John 11:17, Lazarus four days dead as exceptional), and mourning rites began immediately upon death confirmation. Professional mourners (predominantly women) were expected at any respectable household's bereavement. Their immediate presence confirms death has genuinely occurred before Jesus arrives. Jesus's 'do not weep' directly counters the mourning rites — in Jewish convention, telling mourners not to mourn signified either denial or reversal of the death situation.</p>",
"53": "<p>The mourners' laughter at Jesus's statement ('she is not dead but sleeping') reflects their professional expertise — they had seen death and recognized it unambiguously. 'Knowing she was dead' (eidotes hoti apethanen) is Luke's editorial confirmation that her death was not uncertain or misdiagnosed. The mockery parallels dismissals of Jesus's authority elsewhere in the narrative. Their absolute certainty about death's finality is precisely the context that makes the subsequent action a demonstration of divine power over death rather than a medical correction of misdiagnosis.</p>",
"54": "<p>Jesus's taking her hand (kratēsas tēs cheiros autēs) involves deliberate physical contact with a corpse — which under Levitical law would render him ritually unclean for seven days (Num 19:11). The purity transgression is unambiguous and intentional. His willingness to make contact without hesitation signals authority to transcend rather than be subject to the purity system — the same pattern as touching the leper (Luke 5:13) and the Gerasene demoniac's tomb-dwelling. 'Child, arise' (Pais, egeire) uses the standard Greek verb for resurrection, deliberate in its eschatological resonance.</p>",
"55": "<p>'Her spirit returned' (epestrepsen to pneuma autēs) echoes the creation narrative (Gen 2:7; Ps 104:29-30) and specifically Elijah's revival of the widow's son (1 Kgs 17:21-22 LXX: 'the soul of the child returned within him'). The typological echo to Elijah is confirmed by Luke's earlier identification of Jesus as a prophet like Elijah (4:25-26; 7:11-17). The instruction 'give her something to eat' is a practical domesticating detail that confirms genuine bodily resurrection rather than vision, apparition, or coma — she has physical needs that require physical provision.</p>",
"56": "<p>The parents' amazement (existanto — the verb existēmi describes the mind-displacing astonishment of encountering divine action; used in Acts 2:7, 12 of Pentecost; 8:9, 11 of Simon Magus; 9:21 of Paul's conversion report) sets the emotional register. Jesus's instruction to 'tell no one what had happened' follows the messianic secret pattern, here likely reflecting awareness that premature public disclosure of raising the dead would accelerate the crisis of his mission before its appointed time (cf. Luke 9:51 — 'the days were approaching for his ascension'). The secret is strategically temporal, not permanent.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, LUKE_CH8)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'luke', existing)
    ch8_count = len(existing.get('8', {}))
    print(f'Luke 8: {ch8_count}/56 verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
